title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec SU-22
postcontent:
The SU-22 rifle is chambered for the popular and economical .22 Long Rifle cartridge (.22LR). It is based on the 5.56mm NATO chambered SU-16 rifle and shares many parts including the grip and front and rear sights. The SU-22 is not a simple conversion kit, it is a standalone firearm chambered for the .22LR and is designed for target shooting, plinking, or small game hunting. The PLR-22 and SU-22 operate by blowback action and have a 4140 steel bolt that rides on steel guide rails inside the polymer receiver. The ejector is attached to one of the guide rails and the recoil spring is located above the barrel. The cross-bolt safety and magazine release operate identically to the PLR-16 and SU-16.

TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS
Weight unloaded:	4.0 lbs
Length Open:	34"

The PLR-22 and SU-22 will accept many of the same accessories as the PLR-16 and SU-16 including the slings, stocks, and compact forend. The rear sight is adjustable for windage and the front sight is adjustable for elevation. An integrated picatinny rail on top will accept a multitude of sighting options. The muzzle end of the barrel is threaded ½"-28 to accept standard attachments such as a muzzle brake. A 26 round semi-transparent magazine is included and it will accept magazines designed for the Atchison M-16 conversion.

Gun is in great shape, not flawless though.  Has been carried quite a bit in the field (I'm owner #2), but shot very little.  Wood has expected scratches for a 40 year old hunting rifle. title: For Sale/Trade:  Mauser 1909
postcontent:
So I know I`ve been posting and bumping a lot, but my tastes have changed, at least for the moment.
I have a Mauser 1909. It has been sporterized, but is unlike a great many sporters here in the US. the job was done by Chet Paulson out of Tacoma in the late 50s to early 60s. It resides in a handmade stock by Paulson himself, and sports vintage Redfield sights. It is in the original 7.65x53 Argentine, unlike it`s thousands of similar sporters, which were converted to .30-06. In my limited experience, I`ve found that it is a lot cheaper than .30-06 too. The weapon has been used, and it shows. It has no Rust, just some patina on the Bolt face. Mr. Paulson is now deceased, and that only makes this Mauser worth more. Most of his work is in private collections, too. I had it priced at about $700-$750 by a friend who is very knowledgeable on this subject. It only needs a good bolt cleaning, although everything functions exactly as it should.

This is a beautiful old Winchester that will make a fine addition to any collection.  The complex machining of the 1st and 2nd series 1890s really set them apart from the mass produced 3rd series, and gave these earlier guns beautiful, uninterrupted lines.

This particular example has been professionally restored by the late MasterGunsmith Harold Hanson of McMinnville, Or.  Harold has since passed, but his work is renowned in the collector community.  Chambered in 22 Short, this is a gun that is not only lovely to look at and hold, but still very shootable.

More pictures available.

Open for trades of quality shotguns, very large, or very small caliber rifles, handguns, or european optics.
